nodes.name: transmembrane transport
nodes.description: The process in which a solute is transported across a lipid bilayer, from one side of a membrane to the other

nodes.name: drug transmembrane transport
nodes.description: The process in which a drug is transported from one side of a membrane to the other by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

nodes.name: chloride transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of chloride into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

nodes.name: chloride transmembrane transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of chloride across a membrane.

nodes.name: circadian rhythm
nodes.description: Any biological process in an organism that recurs with a regularity of approximately 24 hours.

nodes.name: detoxification
nodes.description: Any process that reduces or removes the toxicity of a toxic substance. These may include transport of the toxic substance away from sensitive areas and to compartments or complexes whose purpose is sequestration of the toxic substance.

nodes.name: developmental process
nodes.description: A biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of an integrated living unit: an anatomical structure (which may be a subcellular structure, cell, tissue, or organ), or organism over time from an initial condition to a later condition.

nodes.name: anatomical structure development
nodes.description: The biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of an anatomical structure from an initial condition to its mature state. This process begins with the formation of the structure and ends with the mature structure, whatever form that may be including its natural destruction. An anatomical structure is any biological entity that occupies space and is distinguished from its surroundings. Anatomical structures can be macroscopic such as a carpel, or microscopic such as an acrosome.

nodes.name: cell development
nodes.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of the cell over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Cell development does not include the steps involved in committing a cell to a specific fate.

nodes.name: bone cell development
nodes.description: The process whose specific outcome is the progression of a bone cell over time, from initial commitment of the cell to a specific fate, to the fully functional differentiated cell.

nodes.name: anatomical structure morphogenesis
nodes.description: The process in which anatomical structures are generated and organized. Morphogenesis pertains to the creation of form.

nodes.name: organ morphogenesis
nodes.description: Morphogenesis of an organ. An organ is defined as a tissue or set of tissues that work together to perform a specific function or functions. Morphogenesis is the process in which anatomical structures are generated and organized. Organs are commonly observed as visibly distinct structures, but may also exist as loosely associated clusters of cells that work together to perform a specific function or functions.

nodes.name: bone morphogenesis
nodes.description: The process in which bones are generated and organized.

nodes.name: single-organism developmental process
nodes.description: A biological process whose specific outcome is the progression of an integrated living unit: an anatomical structure (which may be a subcellular structure, cell, tissue, or organ), or organism over time from an initial condition to a later condition, involving only one organism.

nodes.name: aging
nodes.description: A developmental process that is a deterioration and loss of function over time. Aging includes loss of functions such as resistance to disease, homeostasis, and fertility, as well as wear and tear. Aging includes cellular senescence, but is more inclusive. May precede death (GO:0016265) and may succeed developmental maturation (GO:0021700).

nodes.name: tissue morphogenesis
nodes.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of a tissue are generated and organized.

nodes.name: morphogenesis of an epithelium
nodes.description: The process in which the anatomical structures of epithelia are generated and organized. An epithelium consists of closely packed cells arranged in one or more layers, that covers the outer surfaces of the body or lines any internal cavity or tube.

nodes.name: DNA repair
nodes.description: The process of restoring DNA after damage. Genomes are subject to damage by chemical and physical agents in the environment (e.g. UV and ionizing radiations, chemical mutagens, fungal and bacterial toxins, etc.) and by free radicals or alkylating agents endogenously generated in metabolism. DNA is also damaged because of errors during its replication. A variety of different DNA repair pathways have been reported that include direct reversal, base excision repair, nucleotide excision repair, photoreactivation, bypass, double-strand break repair pathway, and mismatch repair pathway.

nodes.name: double-strand break repair
nodes.description: The repair of double-strand breaks in DNA via homologous and nonhomologous mechanisms to reform a continuous DNA helix.

nodes.name: drug transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of a drug, a substance used in the diagnosis, treatment or prevention of a disease, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

nodes.name: G-protein coupled receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals that proceeds with an activated receptor promoting the exchange of GDP for GTP on the alpha-subunit of an associated heterotrimeric G-protein complex. The GTP-bound activated alpha-G-protein then dissociates from the beta- and gamma-subunits to further transmit the signal within the cell. The pathway begins with receptor-ligand interaction, or for basal GPCR signaling the pathway begins with the receptor activating its G protein in the absence of an agonist, and ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.  The pathway can start from the plasma membrane, Golgi or nuclear membrane (PMID:24568158 and PMID:16902576).

nodes.name: adrenergic receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of an adrenergic receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

nodes.name: apelin receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of an apelin receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

nodes.name: dopamine receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a dopamine receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

nodes.name: G-protein coupled acetylcholine receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: Any series of molecular signals initiated by an acetylcholine receptor on the surface of the target cell binding to one of its physiological ligands, and proceeding with the activated receptor promoting the exchange of GDP for GTP on the alpha-subunit of an associated heterotrimeric G-protein complex. The GTP-bound activated alpha-G-protein then dissociates from the beta- and gamma-subunits to further transmit the signal within the cell. The pathway begins with receptor-ligand interaction and ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

nodes.name: G-protein coupled acetylcholine receptor signaling pathway involved in positive regulation of acetylcholine secretion, neurotransmission
nodes.description: Any G-protein coupled acetylcholine receptor signaling pathway that is involved in positive regulation of acetylcholine secretion, neurotransmission.

nodes.name: G-protein coupled glutamate receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by glutamate binding to a glutamate receptor on the surface of the target cell, and proceeding with the activated receptor promoting the exchange of GDP for GTP on the alpha-subunit of an associated heterotrimeric G-protein complex. Ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

nodes.name: G-protein coupled receptor signaling pathway, coupled to cyclic nucleotide second messenger
nodes.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a G-protein coupled receptor binding to its physiological ligand, where the pathway proceeds with activation or inhibition of a nucleotide cyclase activity and a subsequent change in the concentration of a cyclic nucleotide.

nodes.name: adenylate cyclase-modulating G-protein coupled receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a G-protein coupled receptor binding to its physiological ligand, where the pathway proceeds through activation or inhibition of adenylyl cyclase activity and a subsequent change in the concentration of cyclic AMP (cAMP).

nodes.name: G-protein coupled receptor signaling pathway, coupled to S1P second messenger
nodes.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of an adrenergic receptor binding to its physiological ligand, where the pathway proceeds with activation of sphingosine kinase and a subsequent increase in cellular levels of sphingosine-1-phosphate (S1P).

nodes.name: neuropeptide signaling pathway
nodes.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a peptide neurotransmitter binding to a cell surface receptor.

nodes.name: galanin-activated signaling pathway
nodes.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of the peptide neurotransmitter galanin binding to a cell surface receptor.

nodes.name: opioid receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of an opioid receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

nodes.name: phospholipase D-activating G-protein coupled receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a G-protein coupled receptor binding to its physiological ligand, where the pathway proceeds with activation of phospholipase D (PLD) and a subsequent increase in cellular levels of phosphatidic acid (PA).

nodes.name: serotonin receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a serotonin receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

nodes.name: gene expression
nodes.description: The process in which a gene's sequence is converted into a mature gene product or products (proteins or RNA). This includes the production of an RNA transcript as well as any processing to produce a mature RNA product or an mRNA or circRNA (for protein-coding genes) and the translation of that mRNA or circRNA into protein. Protein maturation is included when required to form an active form of a product from an inactive precursor form.

nodes.name: immune system process
nodes.description: Any process involved in the development or functioning of the immune system, an organismal system for calibrated responses to potential internal or invasive threats.

nodes.name: activation of immune response
nodes.description: Any process that initiates an immune response.

nodes.name: immune response-activating signal transduction
nodes.description: The cascade of processes by which a signal interacts with a receptor, causing a change in the level or activity of a second messenger or other downstream target, and ultimately leading to activation or perpetuation of an immune response.

nodes.name: innate immune response-activating signal transduction
nodes.description: The cascade of processes by which a signal interacts with a receptor, causing a change in the level or activity of a second messenger or other downstream target, and ultimately leading to activation or perpetuation of an innate immune response.

nodes.name: pattern recognition receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a pattern recognition receptor (PRR) binding to one of its physiological ligands. PRRs bind pathogen-associated molecular pattern (PAMPs), structures conserved among microbial species, or damage-associated molecular pattern (DAMPs), endogenous molecules released from damaged cells.

nodes.name: cell surface pattern recognition receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a cell surface pattern recognition receptor (PRR) binding to one of its physiological ligands. PRRs bind pathogen-associated molecular pattern (PAMPs), structures conserved among microbial species, or damage-associated molecular pattern (DAMPs), endogenous molecules released from damaged cells.

nodes.name: toll-like receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of binding to a toll-like receptor. Toll-like receptors directly bind pattern motifs from a variety of microbial sources to initiate innate immune response.

nodes.name: toll-like receptor 4 signaling pathway
nodes.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of binding to toll-like receptor 4.

nodes.name: immune effector process
nodes.description: Any process of the immune system that can potentially contribute to an immune response.

nodes.name: encapsulation of foreign target
nodes.description: Events resulting in the formation of a multilayered cellular sheath surrounding an invader and thus preventing its development. This defense mechanism is often seen in insects in response to nematodes or parasitoids, which are too large to be phagocytosed by individual hemocytes. In some organisms the capsule is blackened due to melanization.

nodes.name: leukocyte mediated immunity
nodes.description: Any process involved in the carrying out of an immune response by a leukocyte.

nodes.name: lymphocyte mediated immunity
nodes.description: Any process involved in the carrying out of an immune response by a lymphocyte.

nodes.name: T cell mediated immunity
nodes.description: Any process involved in the carrying out of an immune response by a T cell.

nodes.name: production of molecular mediator of immune response
nodes.description: The synthesis or release of any molecular mediator of the immune response, resulting in an increase in its intracellular or extracellular levels.

nodes.name: cytokine production involved in immune response
nodes.description: The appearance of a cytokine due to biosynthesis or secretion following a cellular stimulus contributing to an immune response, resulting in an increase in its intracellular or extracellular levels.

nodes.name: immunoglobulin production
nodes.description: The appearance of immunoglobulin due to biosynthesis or secretion following a cellular stimulus, resulting in an increase in its intracellular or extracellular levels.

nodes.name: immunoglobulin production involved in immunoglobulin mediated immune response
nodes.description: The appearance of immunoglobulin due to biosynthesis or secretion following a cellular stimulus during an immune response, resulting in an increase in its intracellular or extracellular levels.

nodes.name: JAK-STAT cascade
nodes.description: Any process in which STAT proteins (Signal Transducers and Activators of Transcription) and JAK (Janus Activated Kinase) proteins convey a signal to trigger a change in the activity or state of a cell. The JAK-STAT cascade begins with activation of STAT proteins by members of the JAK family of tyrosine kinases, proceeds through dimerization and subsequent nuclear translocation of STAT proteins, and ends with regulation of target gene expression by STAT proteins.

nodes.name: localization
nodes.description: Any process in which a cell, a substance, or a cellular entity, such as a protein complex or organelle, is transported to or maintained in a specific location.

nodes.name: establishment of localization
nodes.description: The directed movement of a cell, substance or cellular entity, such as a protein complex or organelle, to a specific location.

nodes.name: establishment of localization in cell
nodes.description: The directed movement of a substance or cellular entity, such as a protein complex or organelle, to a specific location within, or in the membrane of, a cell.

nodes.name: secretion by cell
nodes.description: The controlled release of a substance by a cell.

nodes.name: protein secretion
nodes.description: The controlled release of proteins from a cell.

nodes.name: matrix metallopeptidase secretion
nodes.description: The regulated release of matrix metallopeptidases, a family of zinc-dependent endopeptidases that can degrade extracellular matrix proteins and process other types of proteins.

nodes.name: transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of substances (such as macromolecules, small molecules, ions) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, or within a multicellular organism by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

nodes.name: import into cell
nodes.description: The directed movement of some substance from outside of a cell into the cytoplasmic compartment. This may occur via transport across the plasma membrane or via endocytosis.

nodes.name: inorganic ion import into cell
nodes.description: The directed movement of inorganic ions from outside of a cell into the cytoplasmic compartment. This may occur via transport across the plasma membrane or via endocytosis.

nodes.name: inorganic cation import into cell
nodes.description: The directed movement of inorganic cations from outside of a cell into the cytoplasmic compartment. This may occur via transport across the plasma membrane or via endocytosis.

nodes.name: organic substance transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of organic substances into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, or within a multicellular organism by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. An organic substance is a molecular entity that contains carbon.

nodes.name: lipid transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of lipids into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. Lipids are compounds soluble in an organic solvent but not, or sparingly, in an aqueous solvent.

nodes.name: acylglycerol transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of an acylglycerol into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. An acylglycerol is any mono-, di- or triester of glycerol with (one or more) fatty acids.

nodes.name: triglyceride transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of triglyceride into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. Triglycerides are important components of plant oils, animal fats and animal plasma lipoproteins.

nodes.name: lipid transport involved in lipid storage
nodes.description: The directed movement of lipids into cells that is part of their accumulation and maintenance.

nodes.name: organic cation transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of organic cations into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. Organic cations are atoms or small molecules with a positive charge which contain carbon in covalent linkage.

nodes.name: single-organism transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of substances (such as macromolecules, small molecules, ions) into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, or within a multicellular organism by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore, involving a single organism.

nodes.name: ion transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of charged atoms or small charged molecules into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

nodes.name: cation transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of cations, atoms or small molecules with a net positive charge, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

nodes.name: metal ion transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of metal ions, any metal ion with an electric charge, into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

nodes.name: transition metal ion transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of transition metal ions into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore. A transition metal is an element whose atom has an incomplete d-subshell of extranuclear electrons, or which gives rise to a cation or cations with an incomplete d-subshell. Transition metals often have more than one valency state. Biologically relevant transition metals include vanadium, manganese, iron, copper, cobalt, nickel, molybdenum and silver.

nodes.name: iron ion transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of iron (Fe) ions into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

nodes.name: mitochondrial iron ion transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of iron ions into, out of or within a mitochondrion.

nodes.name: vesicle-mediated transport
nodes.description: A cellular transport process in which transported substances are moved in membrane-bounded vesicles; transported substances are enclosed in the vesicle lumen or located in the vesicle membrane. The process begins with a step that directs a substance to the forming vesicle, and includes vesicle budding and coating. Vesicles are then targeted to, and fuse with, an acceptor membrane.

nodes.name: exocytosis
nodes.description: A process of secretion by a cell that results in the release of intracellular molecules (e.g. hormones, matrix proteins) contained within a membrane-bounded vesicle by fusion of the vesicle with the plasma membrane of a cell. This is the process in which most molecules are secreted from eukaryotic cells.

nodes.name: macromolecule localization
nodes.description: Any process in which a macromolecule is transported to, or maintained in, a specific location.

nodes.name: lipid localization
nodes.description: Any process in which a lipid is transported to, or maintained in, a specific location.

nodes.name: protein localization
nodes.description: Any process in which a protein is transported to, or maintained in, a specific location.

nodes.name: protein transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of proteins into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

nodes.name: intracellular protein transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of proteins in a cell, including the movement of proteins between specific compartments or structures within a cell, such as organelles of a eukaryotic cell.

nodes.name: transferrin transport
nodes.description: The directed movement of transferrin into, out of or within a cell, or between cells, by means of some agent such as a transporter or pore.

nodes.name: metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways, including anabolism and catabolism, by which living organisms transform chemical substances. Metabolic processes typically transform small molecules, but also include macromolecular processes such as DNA repair and replication, and protein synthesis and degradation.

nodes.name: catabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of substances, including the breakdown of carbon compounds with the liberation of energy for use by the cell or organism.

nodes.name: hormone metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving any hormone, naturally occurring substances secreted by specialized cells that affects the metabolism or behavior of other cells possessing functional receptors for the hormone.

nodes.name: peptide hormone processing
nodes.description: The generation of a mature peptide hormone by posttranslational processing of a prohormone.

nodes.name: insulin processing
nodes.description: The formation of mature insulin by proteolysis of the precursor preproinsulin. The signal sequence is first cleaved from preproinsulin to form proinsulin; proinsulin is then cleaved to release the C peptide, leaving the A and B chains of mature insulin linked by disulfide bridges.

nodes.name: thyroid hormone metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving any of the compounds secreted by the thyroid gland, largely thyroxine and triiodothyronine.

nodes.name: nitrogen compound metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving organic or inorganic compounds that contain nitrogen, including (but not limited to) nitrogen fixation, nitrification, denitrification, assimilatory/dissimilatory nitrate reduction and the interconversion of nitrogenous organic matter and ammonium.

nodes.name: organonitrogen compound metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving organonitrogen compound.

nodes.name: dethiobiotin metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving dethiobiotin, a derivative of biotin formed by replacing the sulfur atom by two hydrogen atoms.

nodes.name: organic substance metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving an organic substance, any molecular entity containing carbon.

nodes.name: carbohydrate derivative metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving carbohydrate derivative.

nodes.name: carbohydrate derivative catabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of carbohydrate derivative.

nodes.name: glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate catabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate, an important intermediate in glycolysis.

nodes.name: fatty acid derivative metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving fatty acid derivative.

nodes.name: icosanoid metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving icosanoids, any of a group of C20 polyunsaturated fatty acids.

nodes.name: prostanoid metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving prostanoids, any compound based on or derived from the prostanoate structure.

nodes.name: prostaglandin metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving prostaglandins, any of a group of biologically active metabolites which contain a cyclopentane ring due to the formation of a bond between two carbons of a fatty acid. They have a wide range of biological activities.

nodes.name: lipid metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving lipids, compounds soluble in an organic solvent but not, or sparingly, in an aqueous solvent. Includes fatty acids; neutral fats, other fatty-acid esters, and soaps; long-chain (fatty) alcohols and waxes; sphingoids and other long-chain bases; glycolipids, phospholipids and sphingolipids; and carotenes, polyprenols, sterols, terpenes and other isoprenoids.

nodes.name: cellular lipid metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving lipids, as carried out by individual cells.

nodes.name: cellular lipid catabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of lipids, as carried out by individual cells.

nodes.name: cytosolic lipolysis
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of lipid droplets and hydrolysis of stored triglycerides occurring through the orchestrated activation of cytosolic lipases.

nodes.name: lipid biosynthetic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of lipids, compounds soluble in an organic solvent but not, or sparingly, in an aqueous solvent.

nodes.name: macromolecule metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving macromolecules, any molecule of high relative molecular mass, the structure of which essentially comprises the multiple repetition of units derived, actually or conceptually, from molecules of low relative molecular mass.

nodes.name: macromolecule modification
nodes.description: The covalent alteration of one or more monomeric units in a polypeptide, polynucleotide, polysaccharide, or other biological macromolecule, resulting in a change in its properties.

nodes.name: macromolecule deacylation
nodes.description: The removal of an acyl group, any group or radical of the form RCO- where R is an organic group, from a macromolecule.

nodes.name: protein deacylation
nodes.description: The removal of an acyl group, any group or radical of the form RCO- where R is an organic group, from a protein amino acid.

nodes.name: primary metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving those compounds which are formed as a part of the normal anabolic and catabolic processes. These processes take place in most, if not all, cells of the organism.

nodes.name: carbohydrate metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving carbohydrates, any of a group of organic compounds based of the general formula Cx(H2O)y. Includes the formation of carbohydrate derivatives by the addition of a carbohydrate residue to another molecule.

nodes.name: single-organism carbohydrate metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving carbohydrates, occurring within a single organism.

nodes.name: glycogen metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving glycogen, a polydisperse, highly branched glucan composed of chains of D-glucose residues in alpha-(1->4) glycosidic linkage, joined together by alpha-(1->6) glycosidic linkages.

nodes.name: monosaccharide metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving monosaccharides, the simplest carbohydrates. They are polyhydric alcohols containing either an aldehyde or a keto group and between three to ten or more carbon atoms. They form the constitutional repeating units of oligo- and polysaccharides.

nodes.name: hexose metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving a hexose, any monosaccharide with a chain of six carbon atoms in the molecule.

nodes.name: fructose metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving fructose, the ketohexose arabino-2-hexulose. Fructose exists in a open chain form or as a ring compound. D-fructose is the sweetest of the sugars and is found free in a large number of fruits and honey.

nodes.name: fructose catabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of fructose, the ketohexose arabino-2-hexulose.

nodes.name: fructose catabolic process to hydroxyacetone phosphate and glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of fructose that results in the formation of dihydroxyacetone phosphate and glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate.

nodes.name: glucose metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving glucose, the aldohexose gluco-hexose. D-glucose is dextrorotatory and is sometimes known as dextrose; it is an important source of energy for living organisms and is found free as well as combined in homo- and hetero-oligosaccharides and polysaccharides.

nodes.name: glucose catabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of glucose, the aldohexose gluco-hexose.

nodes.name: rhamnose metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving rhamnose, the hexose 6-deoxy-L-mannose. Rhamnose occurs commonly as a compound of plant glycosides, in polysaccharides of gums and mucilages, and in bacterial polysaccharides. It is also a component of some plant cell wall polysaccharides and frequently acts as the sugar components of flavonoids.

nodes.name: rhamnose biosynthetic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of rhamnose, the hexose 6-deoxy-L-mannose.

nodes.name: cellular amino acid metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving amino acids, carboxylic acids containing one or more amino groups, as carried out by individual cells.

nodes.name: alpha-amino acid metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving an alpha-amino acid.

nodes.name: aspartate family amino acid metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving amino acids of the aspartate family, comprising asparagine, aspartate, lysine, methionine and threonine.

nodes.name: aspartate family amino acid catabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of amino acids of the aspartate family, comprising asparagine, aspartate, lysine, methionine and threonine.

nodes.name: aspartate catabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of aspartate, the anion derived from aspartic acid, 2-aminobutanedioic acid.

nodes.name: aspartate transamidation
nodes.description: The exchange of the amino group of aspartate, the anion derived from aspartic acid, for another amino group.

nodes.name: glutamine family amino acid metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving amino acids of the glutamine family, comprising arginine, glutamate, glutamine and proline.

nodes.name: glutamine family amino acid catabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of amino acids of the glutamine family, comprising arginine, glutamate, glutamine and proline.

nodes.name: arginine catabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of arginine, 2-amino-5-(carbamimidamido)pentanoic acid.

nodes.name: arginine deiminase pathway
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of arginine into other compounds, including ornithine and CO2, using the enzyme arginine deiminase.

nodes.name: protein metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving a specific protein, rather than of proteins in general. Includes protein modification.

nodes.name: cytochrome metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving a cytochrome.

nodes.name: insulin metabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways involving insulin.

nodes.name: insulin catabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of insulin.

nodes.name: proteolysis
nodes.description: The hydrolysis of proteins into smaller polypeptides and/or amino acids by cleavage of their peptide bonds.

nodes.name: protein modification by small protein removal
nodes.description: A protein modification process in which one or more covalently attached groups of a small protein, such as ubiquitin or a ubiquitin-like protein, are removed from a target protein.

nodes.name: protein desumoylation
nodes.description: The process in which a SUMO protein (small ubiquitin-related modifier) is cleaved from its target protein.

nodes.name: proteolysis involved in cellular protein catabolic process
nodes.description: The hydrolysis of a peptide bond or bonds within a protein as part of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein by individual cells.

nodes.name: misfolded or incompletely synthesized protein catabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of misfolded or attenuated proteins.

nodes.name: proteasomal protein catabolic process
nodes.description: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein or peptide by hydrolysis of its peptide bonds that is mediated by the proteasome.

nodes.name: protein deubiquitination involved in ubiquitin-dependent protein catabolic process
nodes.description: The removal of one or more ubiquitin groups from a protein as part of a process of ubiquitin-dependent protein catabolism.

nodes.name: multi-organism process
nodes.description: A biological process which involves another organism of the same or different species.

nodes.name: growth involved in symbiotic interaction
nodes.description: The increase in size or mass of an organism occurring when the organism is in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.name: growth of symbiont involved in interaction with host
nodes.description: The increase in size or mass of an organism, occurring in, on or near the exterior of its host organism. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.name: growth of symbiont in host
nodes.description: The increase in size or mass of an organism, occurring within the cells or tissues of the host organism. This may (but not necessarily) include a filamentous growth form, and also can include secretion of proteases and lipases to break down host tissue. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.name: growth of symbiont in host cell
nodes.description: The increase in size or mass of symbiont, occurring in its host's cell. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.name: interspecies interaction between organisms
nodes.description: Any process in which an organism has an effect on an organism of a different species.

nodes.name: interaction with host
nodes.description: An interaction between two organisms living together in more or less intimate association. The term host is used for the larger (macro) of the two members of a symbiosis; the various forms of symbiosis include parasitism, commensalism and mutualism.

nodes.name: acquisition of nutrients from host
nodes.description: The process that begins with the production and formation of structures and molecules in an organism that are required for the acquisition and utilization of nutrients from its host organism, and the ends with the acquirement of the nutrients. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.name: iron acquisition by symbiont from host
nodes.description: The process by which a symbiont acquires iron from its host, either from heme or other iron containing molecules such as transferrin and lactoferrin. Begins with either the secretion of symbiont gene products that bind iron- or heme-containing molecules (siderophores and hemophores) from the symbiont cell into the host, or by expression of receptors that bind iron- or heme-containing molecules on the symbiont cell surface. Ends when the iron-containing compound is transported into the symbiont cell.

nodes.name: pathogenesis
nodes.description: The set of specific processes that generate the ability of an organism to cause disease in another.

nodes.name: negative regulation of lipid storage
nodes.description: Any process that decreases the rate, frequency or extent of lipid storage. Lipid storage is the accumulation and maintenance in cells or tissues of lipids, compounds soluble in organic solvents but insoluble or sparingly soluble in aqueous solvents. Lipid reserves can be accumulated during early developmental stages for mobilization and utilization at later stages of development.

nodes.name: NF-kappaB import into nucleus
nodes.description: The directed movement of NF-kappaB, a transcription factor for eukaryotic RNA polymerase II promoters, from the cytoplasm into the nucleus, across the nuclear membrane.

nodes.name: platelet activation
nodes.description: A series of progressive, overlapping events triggered by exposure of the platelets to subendothelial tissue. These events include shape change, adhesiveness, aggregation, and release reactions. When carried through to completion, these events lead to the formation of a stable hemostatic plug.

nodes.name: protein phosphorylation
nodes.description: The process of introducing a phosphate group on to a protein.

nodes.name: JUN phosphorylation
nodes.description: The process of introducing a phosphate group into a JUN protein.

nodes.name: negative regulation of protein kinase activity by protein phosphorylation
nodes.description: Any protein phosphorylation process that negatively_regulates protein kinase activity

nodes.name: protein phosphorylation involved in DNA double-strand break processing
nodes.description: Any protein phosphorylation that is required for DNA double-strand break processing.

nodes.name: protein stabilization
nodes.description: Any process involved in maintaining the structure and integrity of a protein and preventing it from degradation or aggregation.

nodes.name: quorum sensing
nodes.description: The process in which single-celled organisms monitor their population density by detecting the concentration of small, diffusible signal molecules produced by the cells themselves.

nodes.name: regulation of gene expression
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression. Gene expression is the process in which a gene's coding sequence is converted into a mature gene product or products (proteins or RNA). This includes the production of an RNA transcript as well as any processing to produce a mature RNA product or an mRNA or circRNA (for protein-coding genes) and the translation of that mRNA or circRNA into protein. Protein maturation is included when required to form an active form of a product from an inactive precursor form.

nodes.name: positive regulation of gene expression
nodes.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression. Gene expression is the process in which a gene's coding sequence is converted into a mature gene product or products (proteins or RNA). This includes the production of an RNA transcript as well as any processing to produce a mature RNA product or an mRNA (for protein-coding genes) and the translation of that mRNA into protein. Protein maturation is included when required to form an active form of a product from an inactive precursor form.

nodes.name: regulation of tRNA processing
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of tRNA processing.

nodes.name: regulation of gene expression, epigenetic
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression; the process is mitotically or meiotically heritable, or is stably self-propagated in the cytoplasm of a resting cell, and does not entail a change in DNA sequence.

nodes.name: DNA methylation
nodes.description: The covalent transfer of a methyl group to either N-6 of adenine or C-5 or N-4 of cytosine.

nodes.name: DNA methylation on cytosine
nodes.description: The covalent transfer of a methyl group to C-5 or N-4 of cytosine in a DNA molecule.

nodes.name: C-5 methylation of cytosine
nodes.description: The covalent transfer of a methyl group to C-5 of cytosine in a DNA molecule.

nodes.name: C-5 methylation on cytosine involved in chromatin silencing
nodes.description: The covalent transfer of a methyl group to C-5 of cytosine in a DNA molecule that contributes to chromatin silencing.

nodes.name: regulation of gene silencing by miRNA
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of the downregulation of gene expression through the action of microRNAs (miRNAs), endogenous 21-24 nucleotide small RNAs processed from stem-loop RNA precursors (pre-miRNAs). Once incorporated into a RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC), miRNAs can downregulate gene expression by either of two posttranscriptional mechanisms: mRNA cleavage or translational repression.

nodes.name: regulation of membrane potential
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the establishment or extent of a membrane potential, the electric potential existing across any membrane arising from charges in the membrane itself and from the charges present in the media on either side of the membrane.

nodes.name: regulation of mitochondrial membrane potential
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the establishment or extent of the mitochondrial membrane potential, the electric potential existing across the mitochondrial membrane arising from charges in the membrane itself and from the charges present in the media on either side of the membrane.

nodes.name: regulation of resting membrane potential
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the establishment or extent of a resting potential, the electrical charge across the plasma membrane, with the interior of the cell negative with respect to the exterior. The resting potential is the membrane potential of a cell that is not stimulated to be depolarized or hyperpolarized.

nodes.name: regulation of molecular function
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of a molecular function, an elemental biological activity occurring at the molecular level, such as catalysis or binding.

nodes.name: negative regulation of molecular function
nodes.description: Any process that stops or reduces the rate or extent of a molecular function, an elemental biological activity occurring at the molecular level, such as catalysis or binding.

nodes.name: negative regulation of ligand-dependent nuclear receptor transcription coactivator activity
nodes.description: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of ligand-dependent nuclear receptor transcription coactivator activity.

nodes.name: negative regulation of sequence-specific DNA binding transcription factor activity
nodes.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the activity of a transcription factor, any factor involved in the initiation or regulation of transcription.

nodes.name: negative regulation of NF-kappaB transcription factor activity
nodes.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the activity of the transcription factor NF-kappaB.

nodes.name: positive regulation of molecular function
nodes.description: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of a molecular function, an elemental biological activity occurring at the molecular level, such as catalysis or binding.

nodes.name: positive regulation of sequence-specific DNA binding transcription factor activity
nodes.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of activity of a transcription factor, any factor involved in the initiation or regulation of transcription.

nodes.name: positive regulation of NF-kappaB transcription factor activity
nodes.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of activity of the transcription factor NF-kappaB.

nodes.name: positive regulation of thyroid hormone receptor activity
nodes.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of thyroid hormone receptor activity.

nodes.name: regulation of binding
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of binding, the selective interaction of a molecule with one or more specific sites on another molecule.

nodes.name: regulation of DNA binding
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of DNA binding. DNA binding is any process in which a gene product interacts selectively with DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid).

nodes.name: regulation of GTP binding
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of GTP binding.

nodes.name: regulation of mRNA binding
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of mRNA binding.

nodes.name: regulation of protein binding
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of protein binding.

nodes.name: negative regulation of protein binding
nodes.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of protein binding.

nodes.name: desensitization of G-protein coupled receptor protein signaling pathway by arrestin
nodes.description: The process that inhibits the signaling function of a G-protein coupled receptor by uncoupling the receptor from its downstream G proteins.

nodes.name: regulation of C-C chemokine binding
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of C-C chemokine binding.

nodes.name: regulation of Ras GTPase binding
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of Ras GTPase binding.

nodes.name: regulation of electron carrier activity
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of electron carrier activity.

nodes.name: regulation of ligand-dependent nuclear receptor transcription coactivator activity
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of ligand-dependent nuclear receptor transcription coactivator activity.

nodes.name: regulation of transporter activity
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the activity of a transporter.

nodes.name: regulation of proteasomal protein catabolic process
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the rate, frequency, or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of a protein or peptide by hydrolysis of its peptide bonds that is mediated by the proteasome.

nodes.name: regulation of proteasomal ubiquitin-dependent protein catabolic process
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the breakdown of a protein or peptide by hydrolysis of its peptide bonds, initiated by the covalent attachment of ubiquitin, and mediated by the proteasome.

nodes.name: regulation of ER-associated ubiquitin-dependent protein catabolic process
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of ER-associated ubiquitin-dependent protein catabolic process.

nodes.name: regulation of RNA splicing
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of RNA splicing, the process of removing sections of the primary RNA transcript to remove sequences not present in the mature form of the RNA and joining the remaining sections to form the mature form of the RNA.

nodes.name: regulation of sequence-specific DNA binding transcription factor activity
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the activity of a transcription factor, any factor involved in the initiation or regulation of transcription.

nodes.name: regulation of transcription, DNA-templated
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cellular DNA-templated transcription.

nodes.name: modulation by virus of host transcription
nodes.description: Any process in which a virus modulates the frequency, rate or extent of its host's transcription.

nodes.name: activation by virus of host NF-kappaB transcription factor activity
nodes.description: Any process in which a virus starts, promotes, or enhances the activity of the host transcription factor NF-kappaB.

nodes.name: negative regulation of transcription, DNA-templated
nodes.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of cellular DNA-templated transcription.

nodes.name: negative regulation of transcription by transcription factor localization
nodes.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of DNA-dependent transcription using a mechanism that involves the localization of a transcription factor.

nodes.name: positive regulation of transcription, DNA-templated
nodes.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of cellular DNA-templated transcription.

nodes.name: positive regulation of DNA-templated transcription, initiation
nodes.description: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of DNA-templated transcription initiation.

nodes.name: positive regulation of transcription initiation from RNA polymerase II promoter
nodes.description: Any process that increases the rate, frequency or extent of a process involved in starting transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter.

nodes.name: regulation of transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter.

nodes.name: regulation of translation
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of proteins by the translation of mRNA or circRNA.

nodes.name: negative regulation of translation
nodes.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of the chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of proteins by the translation of mRNA.

nodes.name: mRNA destabilization
nodes.description: Any process that decreases the stability of an mRNA molecule, making it more vulnerable to degradative processes. Messenger RNA is the intermediate molecule between DNA and protein. It includes UTR and coding sequences. It does not contain introns.

nodes.name: 3'-UTR-mediated mRNA destabilization
nodes.description: An mRNA destabilization process in which one or more RNA-binding proteins associate with the 3'-untranslated region (UTR) of an mRNA.

nodes.name: regulation of translational initiation
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of translational initiation.

nodes.name: negative regulation of translational initiation
nodes.description: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of translational initiation.

nodes.name: regulation of ubiquitin-protein transferase activity
nodes.description: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of ubiquitin transferase activity.

nodes.name: response to hypoxia
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus indicating lowered oxygen tension. Hypoxia, defined as a decline in O2 levels below normoxic levels of 20.8 - 20.95%, results in metabolic adaptation at both the cellular and organismal level.

nodes.name: response to reactive oxygen species
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a reactive oxygen species stimulus. Reactive oxygen species include singlet oxygen, superoxide, and oxygen free radicals.

nodes.name: response to stimulus
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus. The process begins with detection of the stimulus and ends with a change in state or activity or the cell or organism.

nodes.name: immune response
nodes.description: Any immune system process that functions in the calibrated response of an organism to a potential internal or invasive threat.

nodes.name: response to abiotic stimulus
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an abiotic (non-living) stimulus.

nodes.name: detection of abiotic stimulus
nodes.description: The series of events in which an (non-living) abiotic stimulus is received by a cell and converted into a molecular signal.

nodes.name: detection of temperature stimulus
nodes.description: The series of events in which a temperature stimulus (hot or cold) is received and converted into a molecular signal.

nodes.name: detection of temperature stimulus involved in sensory perception
nodes.description: The series of events in which a temperature stimulus is received and converted into a molecular signal as part of sensory perception.

nodes.name: detection of temperature stimulus involved in sensory perception of pain
nodes.description: The series of events involved in the perception of pain in which a temperature stimulus is received and converted into a molecular signal.

nodes.name: response to temperature stimulus
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a temperature stimulus.

nodes.name: response to heat
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a heat stimulus, a temperature stimulus above the optimal temperature for that organism.

nodes.name: cellular response to heat
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a heat stimulus, a temperature stimulus above the optimal temperature for that organism.

nodes.name: positive regulation of transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter in response to heat stress
nodes.description: Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter as a result of a heat stimulus, a temperature stimulus above the optimal temperature for that organism.

nodes.name: response to chemical
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a chemical stimulus.

nodes.name: response to inorganic substance
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an inorganic substance stimulus.

nodes.name: response to metal ion
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a metal ion stimulus.

nodes.name: response to magnesium ion
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a magnesium ion stimulus.

nodes.name: cellular response to magnesium ion
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a magnesium ion stimulus.

nodes.name: response to organic substance
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an organic substance stimulus.

nodes.name: response to cytokine
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cytokine stimulus.

nodes.name: cellular response to cytokine stimulus
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a cytokine stimulus.

nodes.name: cellular response to interleukin-1
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an interleukin-1 stimulus.

nodes.name: cellular response to tumor necrosis factor
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a tumor necrosis factor stimulus.

nodes.name: response to lipid
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a lipid stimulus.

nodes.name: cellular response to lipid
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a lipid stimulus.

nodes.name: cellular response to phorbol 13-acetate 12-myristate
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a phorbol 13-acetate 12-myristate stimulus.

nodes.name: response to organic cyclic compound
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an organic cyclic compound stimulus.

nodes.name: response to etoposide
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an etoposide stimulus.

nodes.name: response to ionomycin
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an ionomycin stimulus.

nodes.name: response to staurosporine
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a staurosporine stimulus.

nodes.name: response to oxygen-containing compound
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an oxygen-containing compound stimulus.

nodes.name: response to thapsigargin
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a thapsigargin stimulus.

nodes.name: cellular response to thapsigargin
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a thapsigargin stimulus.

nodes.name: response to TNF agonist
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a TNF agonist stimulus.

nodes.name: response to toxic substance
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a toxic stimulus.

nodes.name: response to antibiotic
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an antibiotic stimulus. An antibiotic is a chemical substance produced by a microorganism which has the capacity to inhibit the growth of or to kill other microorganisms.

nodes.name: response to tunicamycin
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a tunicamycin stimulus.

nodes.name: cellular response to tunicamycin
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a tunicamycin stimulus.

nodes.name: response to xenobiotic stimulus
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a xenobiotic compound stimulus. Xenobiotic compounds are compounds foreign to living organisms.

nodes.name: response to endogenous stimulus
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus arising within the organism.

nodes.name: response to hormone
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a hormone stimulus.

nodes.name: response to steroid hormone
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a steroid hormone stimulus.

nodes.name: response to corticosteroid
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a corticosteroid hormone stimulus. A corticosteroid is a steroid hormone that is produced in the adrenal cortex. Corticosteroids are involved in a wide range of physiologic systems such as stress response, immune response and regulation of inflammation, carbohydrate metabolism, protein catabolism, blood electrolyte levels, and behavior. They include glucocorticoids and mineralocorticoids.

nodes.name: response to glucocorticoid
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a glucocorticoid stimulus. Glucocorticoids are hormonal C21 corticosteroids synthesized from cholesterol with the ability to bind with the cortisol receptor and trigger similar effects. Glucocorticoids act primarily on carbohydrate and protein metabolism, and have anti-inflammatory effects.

nodes.name: response to testosterone
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a testosterone stimulus.

nodes.name: response to external stimulus
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an external stimulus.

nodes.name: cellular response to external stimulus
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an external stimulus.

nodes.name: cellular response to extracellular stimulus
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an extracellular stimulus.

nodes.name: cellular response to cell-matrix adhesion
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of cell-matrix adhesion.

nodes.name: response to environmental enrichment
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of the provision of a combination of complex inanimate and social stimulations in the organism's housing environment.

nodes.name: response to external biotic stimulus
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of an external biotic stimulus, an external stimulus caused by, or produced by living things.

nodes.name: response to other organism
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus from another living organism.

nodes.name: response to bacterium
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus from a bacterium.

nodes.name: defense response to bacterium
nodes.description: Reactions triggered in response to the presence of a bacterium that act to protect the cell or organism.

nodes.name: defense response to Gram-negative bacterium
nodes.description: Reactions triggered in response to the presence of a Gram-negative bacterium that act to protect the cell or organism.

nodes.name: response to protozoan
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus from a protozoan.

nodes.name: response to virus
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus from a virus.

nodes.name: cellular response to virus
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a stimulus from a virus.

nodes.name: response to stress
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a disturbance in organismal or cellular homeostasis, usually, but not necessarily, exogenous (e.g. temperature, humidity, ionizing radiation).

nodes.name: response to oxidative stress
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of oxidative stress, a state often resulting from exposure to high levels of reactive oxygen species, e.g. superoxide anions, hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), and hydroxyl radicals.

nodes.name: response to topologically incorrect protein
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a protein that is not folded in its correct three-dimensional structure.

nodes.name: response to misfolded protein
nodes.description: Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or an organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a misfolded protein stimulus.

nodes.name: signal transduction
nodes.description: The cellular process in which a signal is conveyed to trigger a change in the activity or state of a cell. Signal transduction begins with reception of a signal (e.g. a ligand binding to a receptor or receptor activation by a stimulus such as light), or for signal transduction in the absence of ligand, signal-withdrawal or the activity of a constitutively active receptor. Signal transduction ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. regulation of transcription or regulation of a metabolic process. Signal transduction covers signaling from receptors located on the surface of the cell and signaling via molecules located within the cell. For signaling between cells, signal transduction is restricted to events at and within the receiving cell.

nodes.name: apoptotic signaling pathway
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals which triggers the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway starts with reception of a signal, and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered.

nodes.name: extrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals in which a signal is conveyed from the cell surface to trigger the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway starts with either a ligand binding to a cell surface receptor, or a ligand being withdrawn from a cell surface receptor (e.g. in the case of signaling by dependence receptors), and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered.

nodes.name: extrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway via death domain receptors
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals in which a signal is conveyed from the cell surface to trigger the apoptotic death of a cell. The pathway starts with a ligand binding to a death domain receptor on the cell surface, and ends when the execution phase of apoptosis is triggered.

nodes.name: TRAIL-activated apoptotic signaling pathway
nodes.description: An extrinsic apoptotic signaling pathway initiated by the binding of the ligand TRAIL (tumor necrosis factor-related apoptosis-inducing ligand) to a death receptor on the cell surface.

nodes.name: carbohydrate mediated signaling
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals mediated by the detection of carbohydrate.

nodes.name: sugar mediated signaling pathway
nodes.description: The process in which a change in the level of a mono- or disaccharide such as glucose, fructose or sucrose triggers the expression of genes controlling metabolic and developmental processes.

nodes.name: hexose mediated signaling
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals mediated by the detection of hexose.

nodes.name: hexokinase-dependent signaling
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals mediated by hexose and dependent on the detection of hexokinase.

nodes.name: cell surface receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by activation of a receptor on the surface of a cell. The pathway begins with binding of an extracellular ligand to a cell surface receptor, or for receptors that signal in the absence of a ligand, by ligand-withdrawal or the activity of a constitutively active receptor. The pathway ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

nodes.name: CD40 signaling pathway
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of the cell surface receptor CD40 to one of its physiological ligands, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

nodes.name: cytokine-mediated signaling pathway
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a cytokine to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

nodes.name: chemokine-mediated signaling pathway
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a chemokine to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

nodes.name: tumor necrosis factor-mediated signaling pathway
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a tumor necrosis factor to a receptor on the surface of a cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

nodes.name: enzyme linked receptor protein signaling pathway
nodes.description: Any series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of an extracellular ligand to a receptor on the surface of the target cell, where the receptor possesses catalytic activity or is closely associated with an enzyme such as a protein kinase, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

nodes.name: leukemia inhibitory factor signaling pathway
nodes.description: Any series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of leukemia inhibitory factor to a receptor on the surface of the target cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription.

nodes.name: immune response-regulating cell surface receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of an extracellular ligand to a receptor on the surface of the target cell capable of activating, perpetuating, or inhibiting an immune response.

nodes.name: lipopolysaccharide-mediated signaling pathway
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by the binding of a lipopolysaccharide (LPS) to a receptor on the surface of a target cell, and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process, e.g. transcription. Lipopolysaccharides are major components of the outer membrane of Gram-negative bacteria, making them prime targets for recognition by the immune system.

nodes.name: peptidoglycan recognition protein signaling pathway
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals initiated by binding of peptidoglycan to a receptor on the surface of the target cell and ending with regulation of a downstream cellular process. The main outcome of the Imd signaling is the production of antimicrobial peptides.

nodes.name: hypoxia-inducible factor-1alpha signaling pathway
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals mediated by hypoxia-inducible factor (HIF1) in response to lowered oxygen levels (hypoxia). Under hypoxic conditions, the oxygen-sensitive alpha-subunit of hypoxia-inducible factor (HIF)-1 dimerizes with a HIF1-beta subunit (also called ARNT or aryl-hydrocarbon-receptor nuclear translocator), translocates to the nucleus and activates transcription of genes whose products participate in responding to hypoxia.

nodes.name: immune response-regulating signaling pathway
nodes.description: The cascade of processes by which a signal interacts with a receptor, causing a change in the level or activity of a second messenger or other downstream target, and ultimately leading to the activation, perpetuation, or inhibition of an immune response.

nodes.name: intracellular receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: Any series of molecular signals initiated by a ligand binding to an receptor located within a cell.

nodes.name: intracellular steroid hormone receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: A series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of a intracellular steroid hormone receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands.

nodes.name: intracellular estrogen receptor signaling pathway
nodes.description: Any series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of an intracellular estrogen receptor binding to one of its physiological ligands. The pathway begins with receptor-ligand binding, and ends with regulation of a downstream cellular process (e.g. transcription).
